Had a lovely visit to @winchestercathedral this week; what a stunning site! Winchester was the original capital city of England in the time of Alfred the Great, and remained the royal capital up until the norman invasion in 1066. Needless to say, alot of amazing history in these walls.

The first image is of the south east end of the cathedral,  and if you think it looks a bit skew whiff, you'd be right. It was built on foundations of peaty soil near the river Itchen, which resulted in a significant subsiding and large cracks appeared at the beginning of the 20th century. It looked like the cathedral would collapse because of the severe strain it was under, but one man, William Walker, underpinned the all the subsiding walls with bags of concrete over 6 years. Due to the levels of water, he had to work in a diving suit in the dark only feeling the way with his hands. 6 hours a day for 6 years.

The second image is of the fantastic medival tiles in the east end. Britain was particularly famed for its terracotta tiles, and they were used extensively throughout the 13th and 14th centuries in both religious and secular buildings. Being made of a very porous material however they are delicate, and in situ medical floors are now rare - so tread with care!
.
.

node.text:
Lovely trip to Whitsand Bay today to explore this grotto underneath Freathy Cliff. Apparently it was hand carved by a man in the 1700s as a cure for gout. ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è To help with reflection and healing he carved passages of the bible over the ceiling. Part of the roof has subsequently collapsed but some carvings are still visible. 
A gate has been added to the entrance which has now rusted to a point where it can no longer be opened. Unfortunately this means that a lot of litter has built up in the grotto as the spot directly outside is popular for picnics. It's a right shame and I hope National Trust Rame Head rangers have plans to clean it up.

Excitingly we hope to launch several more #monumentmonitor sites specifically to document levels of littering at sites just like this (except considerably further north!)
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
I love finding historic graffiti in castle ruins, I feel it sparks a connection to the people who were here exploring sometimes hundereds of years before me. However this is certainly not true of all such marks.

Making unofficial carvings is certainly not new. Through the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries prisoners in the Tower of London did on occasion employ people to carve their 'marks' onto the walls before  their sentence. They allow us unconventional glimpses into lives that would otherwise have been here before us.

I think its is a matter of context and age. Here examples of graffiti in two different @historicscotland sites, Caerlaverock Castle and Machrie Moor stones circles. The former is a castle, ruined for centuries that humans have occupied, explored and made their own. I find it exciting to see someone with my initials visited 300 years ago. I find the example on the machrie plain offensive. The meaning of the circles is one that is lost in our society, and formed by a culture that predates modern writing. Therefore, seeing initials carved into the soft stone appears almost sacrilegious.

Allow me to make myself clear that I am only talking about historic graffiti. There is *never* a reason to carve your initials into any historical sites. This is illegal and if found and convicted carries a very heavy penalty. If you ever find evidence of new graffiti at a historic site please report it to the police and via twitter/insta using #monumentmonitor. 
What are your opinions on historic graffiti? Do you like or dislike it? Are there any examples that you find interesting?

node.text:
What did you do this weekend? I painted a moss smoothie on a paving slab! 
In six of the #monumentmonitor case study sites we will be attempting to measure biological growth, especially that of moss. I am really interested to see exactly to what extent we can measure growth, and as I cant be in Scotland every month measuring it, I am trying to grow some of my own on some new 'heritage' sites. Apparently, to grow moss on a wall all you have to do is blitz live moss, a small amount of water and live yogurt in a blender, paint it on, and wait. Lets see if it works... It makes for a very interesting smell and I advise you to wash your blender thoroughly afterwards! üòÇ Huge thanks to @georgiecmoss for helping me out.
.
.
.
.
#mossmeetsmoss #diymoss #growingmoss #research #phd #phdlife #womeninstem #experiment #heritage #heritagescience
You'll probably need to spray it with water to get it started at this time of year. An experiment better begun in October.

node.text:
Loch Doon is particularly remote, near the edge of Galloway Forest Park, we got very lost on our way there! However the long journey on winding roads are well worth it . The castle is hidden up off the shores of the lake, and you would almost pass it by if you wernt looking for it.

It sits in a designated dark sky area and is therefore a popular area for campers. There is a campervan field up the road (wild campervanning is no permitted around the loch) but occasionally people camp in the castle itself and build fires in the central staircase. 
This is obviously something we want to discourage and hopefully the we can track how often this happens with the monument monitor submissions.
.
.

node.text:
At Drumtroddan today, in the south west of Scotland looking at these fantastic neolithic cup and ring markings.  It wasn't the best light for it (clear evenings and mornings are best when you can get the best shadows) but you can still see the ring markings on these stones. We have absolutely no idea why they were made, but have been found in tombs from 10,000 to 3000 years ago.

You may also be able to see that in the second picture someone has tried their hand at marking the rings out clearer, which is certainly far from ideal. Hopefully with this project we will be able to better track such vandalism.
.
.

node.text:
Loved visiting Clava Cairns yesterday, it's got a really lovely feel to it. The site comprises of three large cairns, two with passageways into the middle that are aligned with setting sun at the winter solstice. 
The site was the original I aspiration for Craig na Dun, the time travelling stones of Outlander fame. From this we are definately seeing the 'Outland effect'. Higher numbers of visitors are causing erosion and stone displacement around the cairns, which we hope the #monumentmonitor submissions will help document.
.
.

At the stunning Tantallon Castle today. Here we want to monitor the middle tower at the front for any signs of plant growth and erosion. It's quite a location, perched right on the edge of the cliff, built by William Douglas in the 1350s. The red sandstone is striking against the green turf and blue sky. As it's so strategically important, its seen a fair few sieges over the years, the last being the civil war.

node.text:
Back from Shetland today and had time to pop to Tarves this morning to check out the Tolquhun (or Tarves) Tomb. This is an interesting one as it used to sit inside the medieval church, but it now sits alone in the kirkyard after the church was rebuilt in the 1700s. The tomb is an excellent example of renaissance carving in North East Scotland.

We are monitoring the water levels in the tomb, as the carvings are alot more exposed to the Scottish elements than they once were.
#TarvesTomb

node.text:
A friend at the forestry commission once told me everyone has their favourite Broch, and I think I just found mine! This is Culswick broch, in the westside of Shetland, with fantastic views over to the island of Foula.

For those south of the border, Brochs are iron age drystone structures that were used as centers within communities (possibly for defensive purposes). There a simply loads in Shetland, and very often within site of each other. They are always well worth an explore! I believe this one has never been excavated.

This is you in a slide!

So exciting to see one of the first signs going up at the Maiden Stone in Aberdeenshire! Thanks to Malcolm, Gavin and Douglas for making this happen.

The Maiden Stone, or Drumdurno Stone, is a Pictish Standing stone dating from around the 9th century. The Picts were resident in Scotland long before and after the Romans, but we know supringly little about their culture. However they left fantasticly carved standing stones like this one scattered across the land mixing pagan symbols with Christian. 
We want to ensure that this enigmatic monument lasts for a further thousand years, and so with this project we aim to document it from different angles and in different weathers to help us assess whether the stone is being eroded. Historic Environment Scotland have taken steps to ensure it has not already, and if you visit in the winter you will find it wrapped in a box to protect it from the worst of the Scottish weather! 
Find out more at monumentmonitor.com

Back down in Cornwall for the bank holiday and walking around these old mines I couldn't resist a quick post! Cornwall has a wonderful albeit quite spread out UNESCO world heritage site thats celebrate the tin and copper mining industry, which 150 years ago made Cornwall the foremost producer of tin, copper and arsenic in the world. 
Walking along the coastpath through Levant and Botallack the main thing we could hear above the crashing of the waves was the birds warbling and the (very occasional) chough. 150 years ago this would have been a very different story. The air would be rent with the hammering thud of the 'stamps' (steam powered machines which pounded the ore into dust), along clatter of engines running around the clock to pump water from the mines.
The mines themselves run 600 meters deep and extend 1.6 miles out to see. Apparently, in stormy weather you used to be able to hear the rocks crashing above you on the ocean floor. The ocean itself would be dyed red in every direction, as the toxic runoffs from filtering the ore was pumped directly into the sea.

Although I love history and spend a lot of time documenting monuments, I am not too sad that this particular area of industrial heritage has become reclaimed by nature!

node.text:
Down in Cornwall for the Easter break and so I figured I would feature some Cornish heritage on here. A 5 minute walk up the road from me is this beauty, Trethevy Quiot.

Trethevy Quoit is a Neolithic burial chamber (or portal dolmen) dating from around 3500 - 2500 BCE. There are several examples of these dotted around the county but in my opinion this one is by far the most impressive. We don't know all too much about who was buried here, when or even how. However, building the structure must would have been an impressive feat of engineering. The capstone alone weighs roughly 20 tonnes! The capstone may have been designed to be slightly tilted, but now slopes at a much steeper angle than it would have done originally, because the most westerly of the supporting stones has collapsed and lies within the tomb chamber itself. It also doubles as a fantastic den for children and adults alike!
.
.
.
.

node.text:
So exciting to be sent these pictures of our most remote site, Ness of Burgi on the southern tip of Scatness in Shetland. It is a defensive fort known as a 'blockhouse fort', dating from the iron age. It is a solid drystone structure entered by a low covering passage and one of only three examples of such forts in Shetland. 
Considering how exposed it is, it is amazingly well preserved. For the next two years we want to use visitors photographs to assess the extent of the erosion of the peat caps on the tops of the forts. However, it will be interesting to see how many submissions we get as, due to its remoteness, visiting it is not for the faint hearted! Hopefully we will use any data collect to help Historic Scotland estimate how many visitors the site gets a year, as it is very difficult to tell.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
Once again wondering about human nature in machrie Moor on isle of arran: 6 stone circles were erected on this small isle, leaving us speculating on how and what for, nowadays.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

Amazing there was so much activity so long ago on this small island. As part of the "crowd sourced " conservation these photos show some of the paths are waterlogged and people are making them wider and it looks like a stone has been moved or stolen from one of the circles #MonumentMonitor

Today we arrived on the Isle of Arran, and we became fast friends. (1) The ferry ride was smooth and beautiful. (2) We spent hours at the Arran Distillery, tasting wonderful whisky and enjoying a tour with our guide Stuart. (3) The tasting room at Arran is what my single-malt-loving dreams are made of. (4) We checked out the Lochranza Castle ruin, which dates back to the 13th century. I liked this dramatic staircase. (5) The lovely view next to the castle. (6) One of the Machrie Moor standing stone circles, which we found after a little over a mile walk through a huge sheep farm. Looking forward to exploring more of this sweet little island‚Äã tomorrow!
